A Linked List is a linear data structure where elements are stored in nodes,
and each node contains data and a reference (pointer) to the next node.
 Unlike arrays, elements are not stored in contiguous memory.

 Array = continuous memory (like seats in a row)
 ➡️ Linked List = chain (like train compartments)

 Singly Linked List
 Each node points to next node
 Most commonly used
 10 → 20 → 30 → NULL

 2️⃣ Doubly Linked List
 👉 Each node has:
 previous pointer
 next pointer
 NULL ← 10 ↔ 20 ↔ 30 → NULL
 Advantage:
 Can traverse both directions

 3️⃣ Circular Linked List
 👉 Last node points back to head

 10 → 20 → 30 → (back to 10)